### Implementing `cache.ts`

The cache module uses the already-implemented S3 client:

```typescript
// packages/core/src/build/cache.ts
import { uploadToS3, downloadFromS3 } from "@gblockparty/shared/backend";
import { createLogger } from "@gblockparty/shared/backend";

const logger = createLogger("build-cache");

export async function saveCache(
  bucket: string,
  projectId: string,
  branch: string,
  lockfileHash: string,
  data: Buffer,
): Promise<void> {
  const key = `${projectId}/deps/${lockfileHash}`;
  logger.info({ projectId, branch, key }, "Saving build cache");
  await uploadToS3(bucket, key, data);
}

export async function restoreCache(
  bucket: string,
  projectId: string,
  branch: string,
  lockfileHash: string,
): Promise<Buffer | null> {
  const key = `${projectId}/deps/${lockfileHash}`;
  logger.info({ projectId, branch, key }, "Restoring build cache");
  return downloadFromS3(bucket, key);
}
```

The S3 key format:
- **Dependency cache:** `{projectId}/deps/{lockfileHash}` -- keyed by lockfile content hash so it invalidates when dependencies change.
- **Framework build cache:** `{projectId}/build/{branch}` -- keyed by branch so each branch has its own cache.
- **Build logs:** `{projectId}/builds/{deploymentId}/build.log` -- one log per deployment.

The existing `downloadFromS3()` already returns `null` for `NoSuchKey` errors (cache miss), so no special handling is needed.

---

### Tarball Helpers

For creating and extracting tarballs (used by cache save/restore), use the `tar` package:

```typescript
import tar from "tar";
import { pipeline } from "stream/promises";

async function createTarball(directoryPath: string): Promise<Buffer> {
  const chunks: Buffer[] = [];
  const stream = tar.create({ gzip: true, cwd: path.dirname(directoryPath) }, [
    path.basename(directoryPath),
  ]);
  for await (const chunk of stream) {
    chunks.push(chunk as Buffer);
  }
  return Buffer.concat(chunks);
}

async function extractTarball(data: Buffer, targetPath: string): Promise<void> {
  await fs.promises.mkdir(targetPath, { recursive: true });
  const { Readable } = await import("stream");
  const stream = Readable.from(data);
  await pipeline(stream, tar.extract({ cwd: path.dirname(targetPath) }));
}
```

These can be added to `cache.ts` or a separate utility file.

**Dependency:** The `tar` package may need to be added:
```bash
pnpm --filter @gblockparty/core add tar
pnpm --filter @gblockparty/core add -D @types/tar
```

---

## S3 Key Structure

After Phase 4, the S3 bucket contains:

```
s3://gblockparty-builds/
  {projectId}/
    deps/
      {lockfileHash}              # dependency cache tarball
    build/
      {branch}                    # framework build cache tarball
    builds/
      {deploymentId}/
        build.log                 # complete build log (scrubbed)
```

---

## Log Format

Build logs have a structured format with section headers:

```
--- Cloning repository ---

Cloning into '/tmp/gblockparty/builds/abc123-def456'...
remote: Enumerating objects: 150, done.
remote: Counting objects: 100% (150/150), done.
remote: Compressing objects: 100% (120/120), done.

--- Detecting framework ---

Framework: nextjs, Mode: server
Package manager: pnpm

--- Restoring build cache ---

Dependency cache restored from S3

--- Installing dependencies ---

Lockfile is up to date, resolution step is skipped
Packages: +850
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

--- Running build ---

> my-app@1.0.0 build
> next build

   Creating an optimized production build...
   Compiled successfully

--- Building Docker image ---

Step 1/10 : FROM node:20-alpine AS base
Step 2/10 : RUN corepack enable && corepack prepare pnpm@9 --activate
...
Successfully built abc123def456
Successfully tagged myapp:a1b2c3d4e5f6

--- Saving build cache ---

Dependency cache saved to S3
Framework build cache saved to S3

--- Build complete ---
```

